<section class="section">
  <div class="toolRoot">

    <header class="header">
      <p class="lede">
        <strong>Look up your average last spring frost date and first fall frost date at the 32°F / 0°C freeze threshold.</strong>
        Use these dates as planning anchors, then make final decisions based on real conditions (especially nighttime lows and soil temperature).
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="card" aria-label="Lookup frost dates by ZIP or postal code">
      <h2>Look up my frost dates</h2>
      <p class="small" style="opacity:0.86; margin-top:6px;">
        Enter a <strong>5-digit ZIP</strong> (U.S.) or the <strong>first 3 characters</strong> of your postal code (Canada FSA).
      </p>

      <div style="display:flex; gap:10px; flex-wrap:wrap; margin-top:10px;">
        <input type="text" id="frost-lookup-input" placeholder="ZIP or Postal Code" autocomplete="postal-code" aria-label="ZIP or postal code">
        <button id="lookup-btn" type="button">Find frost dates</button>
      </div>

      <div id="lookup-result" style="margin-top:10px;"></div>

      <p class="small muted" style="margin-top:12px;">
        Frost dates are <strong>averages</strong>. Freezing (32°F / 0°C) can occur earlier or later in any given year.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card" aria-label="What these frost dates mean">
      <h2>What these dates represent</h2>

      <p>
        Frost dates are based on historical climate normals. They are best used as a stable planning reference:
        not a prediction for this year.
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Last spring frost:</strong> the average date your area stops reaching 32°F / 0°C overnight.</li>
        <li><strong>First fall frost:</strong> the average date 32°F / 0°C returns in autumn.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Your yard can run earlier or later than the average due to wind exposure, elevation, nearby water, urban heat, and cold pockets.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card" aria-label="Use frost dates for planning">
      <h2>What to do with your frost dates</h2>

      <p>
        Once you have your dates, you can turn them into practical schedules:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>Count backward from last frost for indoor seed starts and transplant windows.</li>
        <li>Count backward from first frost to set fall planting cutoffs and harvest priorities.</li>
      </ul>

      <div style="display:flex; gap:10px; flex-wrap:wrap; margin-top:10px;">
      
    <div class="btnRow">
        <a class="button primary" href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Starting Planner (Spring)</a>
        <a class="button" href="/tools/first-frost-planner/">First Frost Planner (Fall)</a>
      </div>

      <p class="small muted" style="margin-top:12px;">
        If you want the “why” behind the numbers, these guides explain how frost dates work and how to use them well:
        <a href="/guides/how-to-find-your-last-frost-date/">How to Find Your Last Frost Date</a>
        and
        <a href="/guides/how-to-find-your-first-frost-date/">How to Find Your First Frost Date</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card" aria-label="Accuracy and limitations">
      <h2>Accuracy notes (what this tool can and can’t do)</h2>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Threshold:</strong> 32°F / 0°C (freeze).</li>
        <li><strong>It’s a baseline:</strong> useful for planning, not perfect for microclimates.</li>
        <li><strong>Location mapping:</strong> ZIPs and FSAs map to nearby climate normals data; local variation still applies.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Practical rule: use frost dates to set your schedule, then use <strong>nighttime lows</strong> to make final go/no-go decisions.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card" aria-label="FAQ">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What does “32°F / 0°C” mean?</summary>
        <p class="muted">
          It’s the freezing point of water. Many seedlings and warm-season crops are damaged at or near this threshold.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Are these the earliest frosts ever?</summary>
        <p class="muted">
          No. These are <strong>average</strong> dates. In some years, freezing arrives earlier; in others, later.
          If you prefer a buffer, plan around the safer part of any planting window.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Why use ZIP/postal code instead of city search?</summary>
        <p class="muted">
          ZIPs and FSAs are fast to type and work well with a static dataset (no APIs).
          If you’re in a mountainous or coastal region, expect more microclimate variation.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Does this work in Canada?</summary>
        <p class="muted">
          Yes. Enter the first 3 characters of your postal code (FSA).
          Frost-based timing applies across cold regions in both the U.S. and Canada.
        </p>
      </details>
    </section>

  </div>
</section>

<script type="module">
  import { lookupFrost, renderResultCard } from "/assets/js/frost-lookup.js";

  const input = document.getElementById("frost-lookup-input");
  const btn = document.getElementById("lookup-btn");
  const out = document.getElementById("lookup-result");

  async function doLookup() {
    if (!input || !out) return;
    const frost = await lookupFrost(input.value);
    renderResultCard(out, frost);
  }

  if (btn) btn.addEventListener("click", doLookup);
  if (input) input.addEventListener("keydown", (e) => { if (e.key === "Enter") doLookup(); });
</script>
